CONVERSATION TITLE: Is it the Right Time for an Executive MBA?
CONTENT:
Hi David,


There‚Äôs a certain point in your career when you‚Äôre ready to think broadly, test the limits, and push yourself forward.


Whether it‚Äôs leadership opportunities, new career prospects, or continued personal growth, you know when you need to stretch and reach for some new perspective. That might be the right time for an Executive MBA (EMBA), a program tailored to the needs of professionals like you that takes your experience and applies it to more advanced concepts. 


Why choose Villanova for your EMBA?


  • World-class faculty who are experts in their fields and bring extensive industry experience to ensure that what you learn is relevant and innovative.
  • A built-in network of peers in the program who bring exceptional talent and experience so that you learn as much from them as you do from our faculty.

Learn More

There‚Äôs a lot to consider with an EMBA. No matter where you are in the thought process, I encourage you to reach out and learn more. Click below and I‚Äôll follow up with more information.


Regards,

Kara Snyder

Associate Director, Executive MBA Admissions

CONVERSATION TITLE: [Permanent + Remote] Senior Full Stack JavaScript Developer
SUBJECT: [Permanent + Remote] Senior Full Stack JavaScript Developer
CONTENT: You might need to see my plan once I create it.¬† If you remember back to our call, using AI effectively requires a wholesale transformation of the way in which developers code. Talking to your collogue this particular role is looking for what I offer, best practices, technologies that enable premium code sharing, patterns that enable code flexibility and reliability, etc... I've got all those tricks in my tool belt too. Moving towards a solid AI development approach not only requires those things to be in place, but benefits from typescript support, monorepo tooling, a variety of automated testing techniques, automated documentation creation, etc...¬†  Like I said I've spent the last year developing almost a completely new way to write code, collaborate with peer developers, developers project managing AI agents, and more, so I'm not exactly seeing it as a tunnel vision.¬† If I want to continue developing this out I need to be able to properly communicate what this is at the outset as it doesn't really exist yet.¬† It's not as simple as just prompting.¬†¬†  And at it's core, the "best practices" I would be recommending now would be heavily influenced by what things need to be in place in the codebase to teach AI Agents how to follow best practices while coding in the codebase.¬† So it's all relevant.¬† The agents are the new juniors I'd be responsible for mentoring, and the senior devs on staff need to learn how to use and manage the agents to 10X their productivity.¬† It's all connected.¬† And since I'm in very new territory I need to come up with a way to communicate this.   I'm selling something people don't know they want yet...

CONVERSATION TITLE: [Permanent + Remote] Senior Full Stack JavaScript Developer
SUBJECT: [Permanent + Remote] Senior Full Stack JavaScript Developer
CONTENT: Hey Jeff. Still interested in the gig.¬† I want to put together some supporting materials.¬† I'm seeing a pattern in general right now.¬† Many CEOs and CTO's adding moving their teams towards AI tools as current objectives or on the roadmap for this year... while many of the developers have no idea what they are doing with these tools.¬† They think they do, and end up deciding the tools are terrible and their bosses are stupid and getting wrapped up in hype. I think there is a significant skill issue going on and before I get hired on somewhere as "just another developer" I really feel my place is as a principal or staff level engineer that specializes in helping the entire team/organization transition towards efficient use of ai coding tools.¬† I need to lay out my vision for this.¬†¬†  Maybe this current gig is a great fit since it's on their roadmap, maybe it's not.¬† But I want to put my best foot forward and throw my hat in the ring for the role I think I should be providing right now.¬† Give me a few days to get my first drafts together of this stuff.  Let me know if you think the whole thing will disappear though if I don't start their process right away though. I'd rather rough it without anything if I'm going to miss out on a shot completely, but in general I see it's important to differentiate one's self these days and I've spent so much time developing my systems I haven't had a chance to articulate them into sales materials for myself until now.  lemme know.

CONVERSATION TITLE: Lead Engineer - Veteran wellness and suicide prevention - The GUIDE App
SUBJECT: Lead Engineer - Veteran wellness and suicide prevention - The GUIDE App
CONTENT: Hello David,  We‚Äôre conducting a high-priority search for a Lead Engineer on behalf of The GUIDE App team, an award-winning Health and Wellness app.  GUIDE‚Äôs mission is to help veterans and first responders recover from and manage deep trauma, with an overarching goal to prevent suicide. Their app is a vitally important, science-backed lifeline that makes mental health and wellness accessible for an extremely vulnerable population.  Our user base is growing rapidly, and we‚Äôll soon open an office in Philadelphia. We seek a Lead Engineer who is passionate about our mission and has strong software development acumen. This position has a 50/50 blend of hands-on coding and leading a team of junior developers. You need to be able to dive deeply into the coding trenches and also be able to look at the bigger picture to mentor and set up repeatable processes for the team. This position is about taking ownership of the successes and failures alongside the team, with the goal of becoming a stronger group of developers along the way. Hey Dave, sorry for the delay in getting back to you - and for my tone in my note - sorry I was (and still am) angry, shocked and disgusted. Thank you for the many kind words, concern, follow up - and I am very sympathetic to everything you shared that you have been dealing with, especially family matters and the messaging/impact and concern that this event poses for you and others remaining at Scala. I truly hope it gets better for you.  I simply have been overwhelmed on a number of levels as this was so unexpected and quite a shock and the timing could not have been worse with my surgery and ongoing recovery and pending holidays, and all the other mass layoffs in the tech world (Meta, Twitter, etc) that I'll likely find myself competing with for a new job depending on what I try to tackle next.  I definitely would like to stay in touch, and connect further, but I simply need a few days to just unplug and deal with some other lingering aspects of my surgery and my layoff that are problematic at the moment. Apologies for my brevity for now.  Hang in there, and I'll reach out soon. Thanks - Rob

Yes this is very concerning news to me. As far as I could tell you were one of the most valuable engineers at the company.¬† Not only did you have your hands deep in R&D, familiar with new tech, but you were involved with many of the product lines across the board. You had a long tenure which gave you great insights into where we were to help chart paths for the future.¬† I watched you overachieve and constantly push into areas and concerns that were being overlooked and that is hugely valuable.¬† You were one of the coolest heads helping to broker understanding between the DC team and Bill and I'm sure a reason why things are running smoother now and Bill is trying to be more empathetic to the emotional needs of the dev team lately.  For what it's worth I've worked at many startups where they shut off all my communication tools upon leaving or layoff and they were much smaller than Scala. It's to stop you from messaging everybody in the company and telling them what you told me or posting an angry rant in public channels that could hurt morale. They know it's a shitty thing to do and are looking to limit the damage it could have to the rest of the teams you interfaced with.¬†  I'm going through a lot right now myself.¬† For the past year almost I've been going through a really crazy divorce with an ex that has serious mental health issues and went the route of trying to destroy me and take the kids out of state.¬† I've largely defended against this, but it's certainly taken a toll on my work.¬† If they are eliminating positions and laying people off I can't imagine I'm immune.¬† I'm also not the lowest paid person on the team. Mark knows I've been struggling with this and it doesn't seem like they showed a whole lot of care around the timing with you being that you just had surgery. Sorry to hear you are still in pain.¬†¬†  I've never heard of an engineer being laid off, certainly not one as decorated as you, that wasn't given severance... With all the legal bills I have right now and child support,¬† being laid off without severance would be beyond terrible for me.¬†¬†  This kind of move really just strikes fear into the hearts of everyone.¬† Your performance reviews were solid I'm sure and you were contributing, you were one of the few that wasn't actually quiet quitting due to all the bs, but then out of the blue they decided to eliminate your position.¬† The holidays are a difficult time of year to find a new job due to¬† time with family and financial obligations and nobody wants to job search without a job. Although I'm sure you will land on your feet with the kind of experience and connections I'm sure you've made over the years.¬† It's hard for me to assume that Scala would make much of a dent in whatever financial problems it's having just removing one engineer regardless of your salary.¬† Difficult not to see this as a signal of greater instability.  I'm not really in a good place to job search myself, but letting you go, for the reasons and the way they did it, is a red flag I almost can't ignore.¬† Up until now I was surfing from one corporate mess to another and this has been the longest I've planted somewhere.¬† The stress and distraction of my divorce has made putting my full attention into something new untenable and still sort of is at the moment.¬† This just adds a whole new front for me to worry about.¬† Ugh...  I'm really sorry to see you go.¬† You were one of the smartest and most useful people I have worked with at Scala. I echo your sentiments about all the others who don't do much and sometimes seem to hinder progress more than advance it. Noting your head butting with Govind the other day around titles when you were just facilitating a meeting to get things done. It definitely does not feel good to lose one of the sanest people both knowledgable about the technical and people issues at the company.¬† You will be sorely missed and I can't imagine I'll be the only engineer gravely concerned for their own safety after watching what they did to you.¬†  If you are interested I can put you in touch with a great recruiter if you don't have someone you have a relationship with and I also have some family with connections at Vanguard if that's a place you think you might want to go. Stable but I know not the most cutting edge. Keep in touch and let me know how it goes for you.  davidmieloch@gmail.com 610-716-4984

Hey Dave, thank you for reaching out. I enjoyed getting to work with you as well, and I am just sorry it has been under less than ideal conditions and circumstances for everyone for so long. I am sorry I couldn't finish talking with you or anyone for that matter earlier today when Slack got cut off right after email. Like who does that at such a small company?¬†  Sorry I am still very angry at the moment hours later at nearly 1:30am. Mark and I were both blindsided, apparently it came down literally to the salary I commanded and EARNED (despite the bullshit "restructuring has eliminated my position" excuse I got from Matt today) and yet you still have clueless turds like Aita and Stephen Booth - clueless total fucksheads.   I have been through this before unfortunately back in 2015, and I know exactly what I am worth based on my experience, capabilities and can command from my job history and experience, and from all the time I put in over the past 6 years here alone to build the services department and then transition to R&D to try and help with our Products. Scala is simply behind in payments across the board and floundering, cant get inventory and clearly fine with attrition and now outright drastic cuts. I literally am one of the only people who was been working on trying to establish a solid foundation for the future of the company since the day I walked in in 2016, and yet Khalif or others recently hired who have done literally NOTHING for months remain - its all money with zero respect and my salary made me a target. unbelieveable, but I have seen this before they think people are expendable, when they are actually your greatest assets.  Scala is a complete joke now - you guys have never even really seen even a small percentage of what I am truly capable of, or what I have done for this company over the past 6 years, and to be unceremoniously simply shut off in the middle of the afternoon literally while I am recovering from major surgery last week (why I was out Wed, Thursday and Friday, I had bi-lateral inguinal hernia repair and am still in a ton of pain but worked all day today) and put in a full solid day of work, to then have ZERO notice, just shut down my email, slack, etc. like I am some sort of scumbag or something that can't be trusted, when I literally had the keys to every single GitHub repo of our entire product lines, infuriates me to no end. Zero respect. This is the company you are employed by.  In any case, despite my grievance, I definitely would be happy to stay in touch, and I wish we could have had more engagement across the board and a more positive experience for you and the rest of the guys working on DC, as it truly is the future of the company. It probably would be easier to convey my thoughts and just follow up with you directly. My cell is 215.901.3142 thats mine and will always follow me and my personal email is rhall@impossibilities.com - I'll drop you a note tomorrow, maybe we can connect when you have some time to chat - I dont have to hold anything back at this point. Probably easier to chat than back and forth here or email. Would be happy to do so.   My only advice, please dont do anything rash in response to my treatment, you are a talented guy with a lot of potential - keep your job as long as you can, I know you have a lot going on, so please don't let what happened to me impact your decisions, but do keep in mind this should be a huge red flag that someone literally working on the future of the company and was passionate about it, is dismissed simply over my salary without even Kevin or Chris reaching out to me to even discuss discuss options, and instead took the chickenshit route of not even speaking to me, and instead having Matt Cadwell a completely useless corporate tool deliver the message - he wanted Mark to tell me and I interrupted Mark asks said to him and Matt: "Mark, I know where you and I stand and my work speaks for it - I want Matt to convey whatever message has been handed down since they cant be bothered to speak to me directly, and I told him him on the phone he is a fuckhead and the entire thing is horseshit - all of this is par for the course. Chris and Kevin dont seem to realize, its not their brand, its not the the products, its definitely not the cheap ass Chinese bullshit bottom of the barrel hardware or any of our outdated intellectual property - its the PEOPLE that make the company - I know this from running my own company for over a decade and my family company since the 1920's. Incredibly myopic and disrespectful and just plain stupid.   ¬†Sorry, clearly I am pretty livid still at the moment regarding everything including the timing and the fact that ALL the feedback from Mark has been positive. ¬†Well connect and chat - again, thank you or being kind enough to reach out and I'll hit you up tomorrow when I can. ¬†Good luck with everything Dave, I feel for you guys. I would suggest if you aren't already looking for another jobs at this point, make sure you have good documentation on what you have done here, and do as much as you can to be prepared because no one is getting severance, only any remaining vacation time. I'm not even getting a bonus I am entitled too for the past year of efforts, nor any of the money I have promised in writing for work I did from day one, on a variety of clients and projects, its been excuses after excuses and I have the documents to back it up. Take care of yourself and stay on your toes. Good luck with everything and well talk soon. All the best to you Dave!
Hey Rob! Stay connected. I noticed they deactivated your slack.  Would you be able to share what exactly happened? I really enjoyed working with you and sorry to see you go.

SUBJECT: Senior Frontend Devr- Perm & full remote - 140-160k base salary + equity
CONTENT: How are you? It's AJ a Headhunter with Randstad. I am working on a special opportunity with well-defined equity. The opportunity is Dragos - https://www.dragos.com/. (please do not apply) Here are my notes from a phone call:  IPO target in 2024.  Not sale or acquisition -- IPO (Talking to banks already).  The job description is attached  More Full stack but focus on front end* 140-160k base salary  All perm, 100% remote, boxcar equity, etc. Sometimes they fly the team members from a department (ie the Infra team) into the Columbia office for a few days to train and team building.  But this is effectively a fully remote role.     Process- Screen with me, interview with the hiring manager, interview with team. Anything over L5 will require additional interviews   The Dragos products live on-site at backbone infrastructure sites (electrical grid infrastructure aka power plants, substations, etc). The Engineering team builds software to spec for each site. So the config mgmt and orchestration are all for the engineering team so that they can build a copy of each customer's config and develop it.     what are your thoughts?  AJ Kuhn Executive Recruiter at Randstad Professionals DIRECT HIRE TECHNOLOGY RECRUITING only and at its FINEST!

SUBJECT: Senior Frontend Engineer (React) | Passwordless Authentication Company ($100mm+ in funding)
CONTENT: Hi David,   I am currently engaged in a search for a Senior Software Engineer on behalf of a rapidly growing cybersecurity/passwordless authentication product company and your background within frontend software development really stood out to me as a great potential fit for this opportunity! CONVERSATION TITLE: Senior Software Engineer, Frontend - FULL REMOTE - React, TypeScript, Functional Programming Environment - Cybersecurity product - 130-160k base + bonus + equity
SUBJECT: Senior Software Engineer, Frontend - FULL REMOTE - React, TypeScript, Functional Programming Environment - Cybersecurity product - 130-160k base + bonus + equity
CONTENT: I wanted to reach out because I was very impressed with your background and wanted to see if you would be open to exploring new opportunities?  Specifically we are working with a Cybersecurity company currently seeking a Senior Software Engineer, Frontend and was wondering if you'd be interested?  You will: -Develop frontend services in our cyber range software platform -Use Typescript for all new code and convert ES6 code as changes are made -Effortlessly handle reactive and responsive user interfaces -Make use of REST and WebSockets to interact with other backend services -Work closely with a passionate team of software developers and designers  You are a good fit if you have: -At least three years of professional software engineering experience, and at least one year of solid experience with React/Redux and Typescript or ES6. Not just side projects or toy problems. -Demonstrated proficiency with HTML5/SASS across browser versions. You must be able to do the basics. -Enjoy making suggestions for new frontend approaches while also working with our existing code base. -Demonstrated understanding of static type systems. All new front-end code is being written in TypeScript, and we refactor the legacy plain JS code to use TS when time allows. -Demonstrated experience with functional programming OR an interest in learning. Our old, untyped JS code liberally uses Ramda, Lodash, etc., and our new TS code is aggressively using libraries like fp-ts, monocle-ts, & newtype-ts, which are inspired by languages like Haskell, Scala, & PureScript. Our backend is written in Haskell, and we try to also write in a FP style on the frontend when possible.  FULL REMOTE - Considering candidates 130-160k base + bonus + equity. US Citizenship required.  If interested please schedule a time to speak further using this link: https://calendly.com/staabr  Ryan Staab Vice President at Robert Half Technology

SUBJECT: Building something new @ Hopper
CONTENT: Hi David,   I came across your LinkedIn profile and wanted to reach out. We're just starting a search to add talented engineers to join our new web team to take on a brand new initiative for us that is critical for our growth in 2021 - building a web portal for travel!  For reference, Hopper started as a travel app. We did about $1B in sales last year and are weathering the COVID storm better than one would expect. We just raised $170M and in the past year have tripled our valuation to almost $2B while growing our revenues by 100%! We owe our success, in large part, to a proprietary suite of data-driven and risk-based financial services that we have developed that complement a customer's trip-purchasing experience. One example is Price Freeze, where our customers are able to purchase a financial option in the app to lock in any price that they see, on any item, for as short as 1 hour or as long as 21 days with Hopper taking the risk on the other side of the trade.  Now we're laying the groundwork to expand from an app to a web product and adding great people to our team who can help us compete with the travel giants.  Would you like to connect and discuss possibilities? Thanks!  Dima Rudov Head of Hopper Web

SUBJECT: 100% REMOTE - Sr. Developer (ag-Grid, Stimulus.js, Rails, TailwindCSS, etc,) @ Allied World Assurance - $$$
CONTENT: Hi there,  My client is the VP of Engineering at Allied World Assurance Company. He is looking for a Sr. Engineer to join a greenfield project and help build an application (a Rails monolith) to power their billion dollar reinsurance business.   The team is taking a very pragmatic approach and trying to keeps things very simple; the current app is made up of 3 modules and uses server-side rendering at its core, with ERB views and sprinkles of JavaScript (Stimulus.js, Turbolinks, Vue components and ag-Grid) on the front end. The current team is predominately Full Stack Rails Engineers and gets into a little bit of trouble out the Rails ecosystem. As a result, the team really needs someone that understands how the front-end architecture fits together and has strong .js skills.    The team is very senior and believes in XP/TDD, modern dev practices. They maintain 100% code coverage (Jest/Rspec) and are running Kanban.   In addition, the team is looking for someone that has strong user experience skills. The overall team has 3 dedicated designers and generally has visual design down pretty well, but when it comes to implementation they don‚Äôt have someone that makes the design still feel good to use and can build in things like animation or motion or focus.  Must haves: - Expert-level knowledge of JavaScript - Strong Rails skills would be a plus  - Experience working with Stimulus.js or ag-Grid - Strong UX skills - Strong knowledge of HTML and CSS - Experience architecting/designing enterprise software  Thanks,  Thanks, Dan dwenzel@beaconhillstaffing.com  Daniel Wenzel Sr. Managing Consultant Beacon Hill Technologies

SUBJECT: 100% Remote, Sr. Frontend Developer   - Allied World Assurance Company - $$$
CONTENT: Hi, Allied World is looking for a Sr. UI/UX Dev and Sr. Frontend Developer to join a greenfield project and bridge the gap between design & dev & help build an enterprise application that powers their billion dollar reinsurance business.    The team is taking a very pragmatic approach: the app consists of 3 modules within a Rails monolith that uses server-side rendering at its core, with ERB views, & sprinkles of JS to bring it all together.  The dev team is staffed with 6 Rails Engineers that get into a little bit of trouble when they leave the Rails ecosystem. The need a engineer w/ expert core JavaScript engineering skills & a dev w/ strong HTML, CSS, and supplemental JavaScript skills that leans more design heavy to join and own the front end UI.  The team is looking to maintain the server side approach and are leveraging Stimulus.js and Turbolinks to pull Rails validations through to the front end.  They are looking to keep the front end as an SRR in Stimulus, and NOT looking to leverage JS frameworks like React, Vue, Angular or go the SPA route   The team is also looking for people that have strong UX skills and a knack for experimentation to find the right solution, even if not formally trained in UX.  The overall team has 3 dedicated designers and has visual design down well, but when it comes to implementation they need someone to make the design feel good to use and build and test things like animation, motion or focus + componentizing the UI.   This is a long term consulting role and 100% remote. I can pay a very competitive rate, either w2 or c2c. Please advise if you‚Äôd like to hear more.    - Expert JavaScript skills - Expert HTML & CSS skills  - TDD/BDD practitioner (the team currently has 100% code coverage) - Familiarity with React, Vue, Ember, etc.  - Strong UX skills  - Experience building enterprise software   Thx, Dan  Daniel Wenzel Sr. Managing Consultant Beacon Hill Technologies

The others are much smaller one is a vanilla js view. Very similar backend but the front end is made with no framework. That one is a virtual coding journal. The other is a dms (system I currently use to write repair orders at work). It‚Äôs a backend only but much heavier built with rails. The view are built with erb and renders via the Controllers and feathers the most complex mode relationship. It is the most textbook representation of rest and includes a 2 type authentication and Facebook oauth. However I think Facebook dropped my oauth because of Inactivity

My most recent is my react project. It‚Äôs a virtual D&D character sheet that can be fully updated and persist all the data. Basically eliminates the need for pen and paper. It gets annoying to write erase over and over again. The project is built with a rails backend. Very light and simple api build( built with the rails new starting build ) only has 4 models/tables and very simple relations (although one of my tables is pretty complex). Standard mvc build where I have a controller for each model. I made my own serializers because it allowed me to further control what gets sent to the view via json as well as allowing me to build on the relationships to make it cleaner and simpler. The front end it built with react and redux. I‚Äôve got 2 containers one responsible for displaying ‚Äúcharacter cards‚Äù basically like an index view. The other responsible for holding a collection of everything else. Stats,spells, attacks, items each one is a collection of components responsible for displaying something. I tried to use separation of concerns for the display components however some of them have render other components that are responsible for performing the update or a task of some form. I used forms built write into this show page to add new things to each character. And I built my own functions to make each and every piece editable.

I was connected to Comcast through a recruiter but never ended up interviewing. I was worried about being furloughed since they mostly hire contractors. I'm glad I decided against it could have lost my job right away after covid.   The biggest companies around here are Comcast and Vanguard, but there are lots of smaller companies worth working for around here too. You just need to get connected to the recruiter scene down here.    I randomly got called in NYC for my last job and worked remote from Manhattan to Conshohoken, PA. Wasn't really sure what was around. After I moved was able to get connected to different recruiters through coworkers and was able to branch out and find more positions. I was surprised how much react work there was.  You will likely end up being full stack at any smaller company or team. The only time where title really limits you is at a big company where there are enough people to cover each piece. Otherwise you'll always be doing a bit of both.   At my current job everybody is a full stack dev but we each lean one way or the other. After flatiron you should be leaning front as backend folks have likely not been introduced to alot of the react and redux patterns.   What are your flatiron projects?

I was in the first 15 week web design cohort and likely did a similar program to the one you did.  Lots of react jobs out here. I'm full stack but many companies are light in serious frontend developers right now (as well as QAE and DevOps). All the good programmers on staff were backend and the backend guys could get away with making a simple frontend, writing tests, and setting up their own DevOps... But it's just too much now and the back end focused guys are putting up the white flag. I'm seeings this pattern again and again. Both this job and my last I came in to refactor and rewrite a front end that a back end engineer wrote.  The patterns are different and they always trying to make MVC happen inside the V (react) layer of the project. That said, I've already worked on the backend and implemented DevOps processes so despite the title I'm not relegated to frontend.  The MERN stack is hot. I see it being used everywhere. Rails was great to learn at flatiron but besides a legacy project I did at my first job, I haven't worked on a single greenfield project that uses rails. Anytime I see a company hiring for rails it's because they have some ancient dying system that the current lead decided to escape from and now they need someone new... sounds fun right? These days seems like everyone uses node. If you are savvy in JavaScript it just makes more sense to use that anyway. Less context switching between languages.  Does not hurt to know some MongoDB and GraphQL. Know Redux, most companies use it and knowing good state management practices is just as important as knowing how to build components with React.  I moved to the Philly burbs. Seems like there were more jobs in the city but after living in Manhattan I didn't want to pay the Philly taxes. 4 days after I started my current job they sent us all home for Corona and have been working from home since.   When you are ready to start looking I can connect you with a recruiter or two down here.

I'd start by coding along with a tutorial on Udemy.¬† I've done a lot of this guy's courses. His name is also Dave which means he's awesome.  https://www.udemy.com/course/react-js-mastering-redux/  https://www.udemy.com/course/react-redux/  Usually along with React you want to know a state management library. Redux is the most popular.  A year and a half ago I did a project for a react agency, they gave me a write up for making a quiz game. I've been modifying it and updating it each job search (haven't updated it this time around yet though). When a company tries to give me their own code test I ask if I can substitute my own code.¬† Better to fight on your own turf than risk that they ask you one of the millions of possible questions that you might not know.  https://github.com/drumnation/react-native-reactjs-quiz-challenges  The purpose of the quiz game app is to show knowledge of state management and react concepts but in a simple app that can easily be understood by the interviewer.  If you wanna meet up for a coffee at some point we can trade further wisdom :D  -Dave

I was just dipping my foot in the water when I posted in Philly devs and going slowly. Having just moved here and bought a house I'm knee deep in renovations and juggling the sleeplessness of having a 1 year old son. That said, our CEO just offered anyone who wanted to leave a 1 month severance and I took the deal on Friday.¬†   I've been talking to a number of recruiters and Comcast was definitely one of the options presented.¬† I'm open to Comcast especially if you're saying it's generally a good gig.¬† I didn't get a DM from Josh, but am looking to network with anybody right now to get the lay of the land.¬† I grew up in Valley Forge, but I've been in the Manhattan tech scene for the last 10 years, living in the East Village, so it's all brand new to me here.  With your situation, I would just make a personal react project that demonstrates using apis, best practice file structure, clean javascript code, etc... and make that the focus of your next react interview. With the way your linkedin profile reads down all you should need for a React gig is to add the word React to it and be able to prove it by showing off some code.¬† I have interviewed a lot of react devs in my past few roles and that was my first impression.   9.5 years at Comcast is nothing to sneeze at. My first impression was that you must be solid to have been there that long.¬† Even if the framework thing is holding you back, I'll bet you that it's kind of the only thing holding you back.¬† Don't wait for other people to give you experience. I got my first React job demoing a personal project.

I'm sure I could pick up react (or angular or vue or web components or whatever), but nobody wants to give me that opportunity. They only want people who are already using it. The project I was working on used the crappy hack of a pseudo framework called riot, which I was able to learn, but that doesn't do me any good. If I'd learned polymer, even that probably wouldn't get me anywhere. I'm not even being that fussy about salary. Anyway, enough about me.¬†  I didn't realize you were still looking. I'll try to go through some of the jobs I didn't get and see if you have better luck. Are you interested in working for Comcast? They have TONS of jobs and lots of them require React. While I think what they did to me was pretty hinky, I have to say it was a pretty sweet gig while it lasted. Their benefits & perqs are awe$ome. You can set up ¬†job searches and get new jobs that match your criteria emailed to you every day.  If Comcast doesn't appeal to you, what are you looking for? I've seen some React jobs here in KoP and other places nearby. I'll try to dig them up and see if they're still open.  I can also connect you with some recruters I've talked with. Did a guy named Josh Hartshorne contact you through Slack by any chance? If not, you might want to connect with him here.

David, this is great insight! I was not looking at it that way. I bombed a couple algo based tech interviews and the experience was definitely not fun. At least for my first developer role. But it definitely makes sense about showing them your work to convey that you have the skills to do the job, or at the very least you can learn the skills to do the job.

Run out the clock leading them through your code samples and then you avoid some random question you may or may not get right. Lower your risk by learning the interviewer through things you know, rather than risk they ask you something you don't know.

The best way to get in is to avoid as much of the technical interview that you can. Try to lead the interviewer through a bunch of prepared code samples and make the whole interview on your own turf. Code wars type problems are only easy if you've solved the problem before.  Keep showing them details and explaining why you chose things and why you organized the code a certain way.  Show them clean code, show them good file structure and architecture, show them react, show them redux.  By the end they should understand that you can do the job.  IMO the code wars style of code testing is kind of dumb, white boards too. None actually demonstrate knowledge of things used in your actual work.

Hey David,  How are you?  Here is the spec for that start up role we mentioned.  Let me know what you think:  Technical Job description   Hello fellow engineers and future teammates,  We are making advances in the field of applied conversational experiences for messaging. Our platform implements true mixed-initiative dialog, which is not possible with stock AI frameworks or services. Being able to fuse realistic human-like conversation design (‚Äúcharacter‚Äù) and NLP/ML with the ubiquity of SMS/MMS (and RCS/Business Chat soon) is why we get out of bed in the morning as engineers at OM.  It‚Äôs also nice that goal-oriented conversations are like little conversion funnels, which makes for deeply meaningful metrics. If you‚Äôre into analytics, this is the lifeblood of our prioritization and decision making so there is a lot of interesting and impactful stuff to do there.  If you‚Äôre into massive scaling and operations, we are currently humming along at thousands of messages per second and have a roadmap to get to millions in the next few months. We need your help to get there.  For the design-inclined, one of our major features is the conversational composer frontend with previews/canvas drawing etc. that will evolve according to what the messaging channels can support in terms of content types and interaction. Messages are personalized in different ways.  We are hooking commerce functionality into the conversations as well. Buying products this way is a lot of fun as a user. Thanks to our design, we can kick off any kind of API calls as a natural part of the conversation without adding complexity to the codebase.  Our current tooling is a mix of Python, Node, PostgreSQL, Redis, Elasticsearch, and Docker. We are exploring Go for some things and prefer smaller abstractions, less frameworks, minimal dependencies, and leveraging purpose-built components. We value orthogonality and safety as design principles. Creativity is best applied to data structures and decoupling.  We are strongly motivated by inclusiveness of all genders, faiths, origins and backgrounds and are careful about ensuring a harmonious and respectful team culture with space for every voice and safety in mutual vulnerability. We value work life balance, boundaries, and privacy as well.  The engineer will get between .05 and 1% of equity in the company and will be one of our early stage members who we hope will evolve into one of the company leaders.   Company description and Perks of working for OpenMessage (feel free to share the below with interested candidates)  OpenMessage is the world's first fully-customizable mobile messaging platform. We evolve black-and-white exchanges into vivid connections, wherever your audience may be. You can visit our site at www.openmessage.io. I have attached an intro deck that you can share with interested candidates. Lastly, here is a link to a video that the founder of TXT Stories created for us illustrating the future of text messaging that we are creating. Jake and I premiered the video this past year on stage at AdWeek during a talk we gave about OpenMessage (The video has been a valuable recruiting tool).    The company's lead investor is Loeb.NYC (Michael Loeb founder of Priceline.com) and has office space in Midtown Manhattan. Bonin Bough (Youngest fortune 50 C-suite executive in history, host of CNBC's the Cleveland Hustle, and NY Times best selling author of Txt Me            (646) 759-1837    ), is a Co-Founder of OpenMessage and our Chief Growth Officer.   In addition to working at an exciting startup, other perks of joining OpenMessage include: Access to both Bonin Bough and Michael Loeb.  Access to OpenMessage's world class advisory board that includes: Tech advisor - Alex Moukas (over 1B in exits, founder of Velti, and Wappier), PR/Marketing - Marcy Simon (Former managing director of Burson & Marsteller), BizDev - Jason Oates (Co-Founder of Live Intent), Tech Advisor -  Jonathan Hyman (Co-Founder of Braze). *Alex Moukas has a hands on role with the tech team. Whoever we hire will get to work with him frequently and can reach out to him with questions mentorship needs.   A beautiful office space with fully stocked kitchens on every floor, lounge, and outdoor work areas.  Company parties at Michael Loeb's house in the Hamptons (Set of the TV show Billions)  A great and exciting startup culture  Comped Seamless lunch account every day and free pizza on Fridays  Monthly speaker series at the office (Additionally lots of well know entrepreneurs, celebrities, and business people visit the office often)  Some of the Clients who we are currently working with  MassAppeal, Hypebeast, The PGA Tour, Comic Con, AdWeek/BrandWeek, Townsquare Media, SingleCare, Blade, Keurig, the Weather Channel, and both major political parties.      Let me know what you think?  Nat

SUBJECT: Please Help
CONTENT: Hi Heidi,  I can't find any way to contact a real person at Handybook. As a developer my wife and I have found a flaw in your system I'm sure you'd want to know about.  Being that you're the only person at Handybook on Linkedin, you're the only person I'm able to contact.  The last three times we've used your service your ratings system has proved to be irrelevant.  We chose a cleaner that was highly rated, but without warning, right before our appointment, our cleaner was switched with a cleaner with no ratings at all.  These new cleaners all three times were terrible.  My wife is pregnant and as a busy software developer and husband I'm doing a lot of cleaning and managing of the house.  These terrible cleaners come into our tiny 2 room apartment that I've kept mostly clean myself and follow your basic checklist as if they have no brain of their own with which to judge what should be cleaned.    I feel it's incredibly unfair that we book a highly rated cleaner only to be bait and switched to a brand new terrible cleaner at the last minute, and then after they barely clean the apartment, get our fee. I came home to hairballs in the kitchen and the house barely much more clean than I left it when I came home.  I realize you're not in the US and thus might not care at all, but I figured I'd reach out to a real person who cares about the company to see if you could remedy our situation, at the very least change the system which allows a chosen cleaner to be switched without our consent at the very last moment instead of offering us the ability to reschedule the highly rated cleaner.  I'd really appreciate a response, even if it's that you can't help me.  Thank you.  -Dave

SUBJECT: Employment Opportunity - Sr. Full Stack Engineer
CONTENT: Hi David,   Hope you‚Äôre having a great day!   I am reaching out to you regarding a Sr. Full Stack Software Engineer role with one of our top business platform/applications provider clients in New York, NY.  This is a full-time opportunity that offers a great salary as well as full benefits, 401K, and some quarterly bonuses. If you are interested in hearing more about this opportunity, please give my recruiter, Zoe Tanzman, a call at the office when you are available. The office number is 213-404-4158 and her email is zoe.tanzman@insightglobal.com.   If you are not interested but have any referrals, I would be more than happy to connect with them as well. Below are some of the qualifications for this position.  Must-have *  - 3+ years of Software Engineering experience, fullstack preferred  - Senior level in JavaScript and have worked with React and Ember.JS - previously built own components and complex JS web applications   - Strong experience with Ruby on Rails and or Elixir, previous C# knowledge is useful also   - Strong in writing scalable services, JSON APIs, and some GraphQL APIs   - Lengthy background in building cross-browser, responsive HTML and worked with modular CSS architecture like ITCSS or OOCSS  Day-2-Day *  An employer is looking for several Sr. FullStack Engineers in NYC or Stamford, CT. These engineers will be responsible for building main features on a series of platforms and applications for our clients customers. The frontend and backend are built in Ember.JS and Ruby on Rails/Elixir along with Phoenix backends. Thanks Brad.  How this would work is a college would purchase a license for the software and every teacher would be given a teacher account and every student given a student account.  At the beginning of the semester all of the composition students would create projects to work on with their private teacher.  You would want to use this so that you could extend your ability to discuss the student's compositions outside of the classroom to make more time for more important in-person discussions.  You'd want to use this to keep a clear history of all revisions on the composition and all related discussions. (Dr. Hanning has us had us keep a lesson log book...this is that for composition)  Right now the closest thing to this tool is SoundCloud, but soundcloud is not designed to do the task of serious collaboration about music. SoundCloud is designed to say "YEAH! AWESOME!" and not have a discussion about a part in a composition.  Just to be clear everything I sent you was for Advertising. The software helps a creative director at an advertising company do his job better. The process of collecting demos, paying demo fees, choosing a winning composer, getting licensing docs, etc... is a huge hassle without a tool designed to put everything in the same place and help you talk digitally about music.  I'm getting feedback from other musicians and composers because I think this could help in a college setting. If i get enough positive feedback from WCU professors and friends, I will recommend that we develop a new version of this software specifically designed for colleges. It will have more features that are even better targeted to a college environment and all the language in the software will change to be appropriate.  Does that make any better sense?  This arose originally from me wanting to post the latest mixes of my band's album online and have a discussion. I tried out SoundCloud for this and it was ultimately too confusing for our engineer to simply read down the list of comments, implement the fixes to the recording, and mark them as complete.    - Contextual comments based on time - Threaded comments (like an email or forum thread) - File Storage and Version Control  The tool is best suited for anyone with a high volume of original compositions/tracks to manage: like a recording studio, music publisher, music label, advertising agency, video production studio, video game developer, television studio, or composition professor.  Keep the feedback coming, if you don't get it then it's a sign that I'm explaining it poorly or it's something that isn't wanted/needed.  Thanks Dude.

I feel like in an educational environments the tool could be really useful because a lot of revisions and discussions about a piece happen over the course of the semester or two (more than working on a 30 second ad track due in 2 weeks.)     In addition there's really no effective way to discuss music online that isn't cumbersome and inefficient. I tried SoundCloud with my band but it's just not meant for real discussion and became really confusing with many comments since they are all sorted by recent instead of track time.     Being able to have productive micro-discussions with your teacher offline could make the in-person lesson more productive and focused on things that can't be communicated digitally very well, like playing something on the piano.

SUBJECT: Digital Marketing Director opportunity
CONTENT: Hi David,  Please excuse the direct mail. We are conducting a Marketing Director search for a well-funded VC backed high-growth (20% month-on-month user growth) SaaS company expanding their team in New York. Your strong experience in digital marketing is exactly what our client is looking for, and as this is a very exciting time to join our client I thought this role could be an interesting next step for you.  The company has recently raised $2.5m to expand their marketing capabilities and is looking to hire a Digital Marketing Director to lead the customer acquisition and retention efforts. The company is seeking a savvy, driven, hands-on individual who is excited to join a highly agile and fast-paced environment. The role includes owning the following responsibilities: Demand Generation, Affiliate Marketing, Engagement/Retention Marketing, touchless sales, SaaS, User Acquisition, Online marketing, SEO/SEM.  Responsibilities -	The development and implementation of a Brand strategy that increases engagement and raises awareness -	Plan and execute all web, SEO/SEM, marketing database, email, social media and display advertising campaigns -	Define, set up and implement acquisition channels for customer segments/personas -	Drive efficiency, develop and test new channels, including content marketing creation and distribution -	Collaborate with internal teams to create landing pages and optimize user experience -	Create the marketing strategy for new and existing products in cooperation with all teams -	Continuously analyze the conversion funnel and identify areas where new strategies can be implemented to increase user acquisition  I hope you don‚Äôt mind me reaching out to you regarding this opportunity in case it is of interest. Would there be a good time for us to arrange a call to discuss the role and company in more detail?  I look forward to hearing from you, Regards Brett

Hi David,   Thanks for connecting. I am recruiting for a Sr. Content Marketing Manager at Movable Ink (www.movableink.com), one of the fastest growing startups in NYC and a leading agile email marketing technology company, and was wondering if you might be interested?   Please find the description below. If interested, please send me a copy of your resume and availability for a phone call to discuss further.   Thanks!   Adam Rose  Director, Executive Search & Recruitment  eCommerce Placement  646.675.6748 | www.ecommerceplacement.com  adam.rose@ecommerceplacement.com   Why Join Us   Do you love the craft of writing? Can you make words sing? Do you have strong opinions about the future of marketing? We live in exciting times and believe that all marketing will be real-time and "in the moment". Movable Ink is building the future of marketing: software that gets out of the way and allows the marketer to deliver personal experiences at massive scale.   Great content is the fuel that feeds our growth engine. We need an expert to create unique thought leadership and research pieces on where marekting is headed. If you‚Äôre excited by this prospect and in crafting the stories to drive our inbound evolution, Movable Ink is where you need to be.   What You'll Be Doing   Movable Ink is looking for a Senior Content Marketing Manager to join our marketing team/growth initiative. This position will oversee and create thought leadership content and help craft inbound content initiatives to drive prospects to our site. We‚Äôre looking for a seasoned writer and producer that can execute on strategic company goals for inbound, had unique thoughts about the industry, and can champion Movable Ink as a leader in the agile marketing space.   Additional "day in the life" activities:   - Build a world-class thought leadership and content marketing program aimed at generating leads, increasing awareness and championing the Movable Ink brand  - Help define the future of digital marketing by painting an accurate, forward-looking view of Movable Ink's suite of real-time targeting, measurement and personalization tools which allow brands to market in the moment  - Help marketers identify which strategies and technologies matter and the steps to take today to drive economic value by developing the right campaign tactics  - Deliver monthly webinars  - Own the execution of the strategic marketing calendar   The Ideal Candidate   Bachelor‚Äôs degree in a related field such as marketing, market research, communications, consulting, strategic planning, journalism or business analysis, preferably in the technology industry and at least 4-7 years of experience in a similar environment   Demonstrated versatility in writing formats, including articles, research reports, point of view papers, summaries, abstracts, blog posts, tweets and more   Ability to translate data into meaningful information and marketing recommendations   Strong client interviewing and research skills   Social media savvy   Ability to multitask and manage complex projects   Highly organized and detail oriented   Solid interpersonal and presentation skills   Benefits   Cool office space located in the Flatiron District  Unlimited vacation days  A brand-new MacBook Air and other goodies to use on the job  A fully-stocked fridge and snack cabinets  A beer keg and a cold brew coffee keg  Foosball, shuffleboard, and ping pong tables   About Movable Ink   What happens in the moment influences how we act, and how we remember it. Shouldn‚Äôt marketing do the same thing? Movable Ink enables brands to market in the moment with real- time digital content delivered at scale in email. Hundreds of innovative brands such as American Eagle Outfitters, Time Inc., Lilly Pulitzer, and Finish Line have increased engagement, conversions, and ROI by using Movable Ink‚Äôs agile marketing solution to plan, create, and execute campaigns that adapt to each individual consumer the instant they engage. The company is headquartered in New York, New York with an office in London, England. For more information, please visit http://www.movableink.com

I think it's a combination of inbound marketing, using landing pages with targeted google adwords and linkedin ads to drive traffic.    You get a more sophisticated (and more expensive) lead tool like Rainking.  This way you get right to the meat.  They have researchers that call the clients and interview them about what their problems are, what hardware they have, and what they are looking to buy in the next 6-12 months.  Then you coordinate landing pages, an email blast to the client, with cold call follow up.    This allows you to make far less calls because of better quality leads, since there is more information about the client so the call isn't quite so cold and you are getting people who are potentially interested.    It's about buying sophisticated tools to cut through the enormous amount of work you'd have to do randomly calling the wrong people all day.    Get people to contact you via the web + cold call the right people using the best information possible so you don't waste your time.      The same problems are happening everywhere.  It just depends on how willing the company is to adapt and spend lots of money on things that didn't used to be necessary.  Marketing, Marketing Automation Tools, Web Development, Quality Lead System, etc...    This has been my experience so far.    -Dave

Yeah Basically.  In the future when the top down hierarchical business model dies the prevalent model will be appropriate scale (global perspectives) meaning that companies will inflate their numbers with contractors when they need them instead of establishing huge repositories of employees.  So how does one get hired in a freelancer world? You need have a resume with some good experience and lots of people who will attest to your value...much like buying a product on amazon.com....humans are becoming amazon.com products.  Building up your profile now little by little I think could prove to be very important someday.  When people all of a sudden realize that this modern form of a resume that is interactive and holds far more information than a normal paper sheet is the way to go they will be shit out of luck because you can't build a huge repository of testimonials over night.  These testimonials are like your "reviews" if you were an amazon.com product.  Really this is the only way a complete stranger over the internet will have the confidence to hire you...same as you have the confidence to buy a product you've never seen or touched before because of the information presented online.    My 2 cents.  Take it or leave it.  Felt you would be a good candidate for this sort of networking and should get on the bus asap.

Hi David -  Thanks for connecting with me, it's much appreciated! I spent some time going over your profile and I think that your expertise is just what I'm looking for.  Datacate provides platform and infrastructure technology solutions. In response to our clients' repeated calls for a cloud services platform that provides a less complicated and costly alternative to AWS, Azure and IBM, we've recently introduced the Datacate cloud services portal. Datacate's approach is to provide a cloud services platform that combines multiple services that a typical company would require, so that they can all be managed in a single pane of glass. Of course we have compute and storage, but we also have content delivery, BaaS and server monitoring all available via the same platform, with more services to be added soon.  Would you be interested in test-driving our new cloud services platform? I'd give you a 30-day pass to try out some features and deployments at no cost to you; you tell me what you like and don't like about it, rate the value, things of that nature. There's no obligation, but if you find the services to be useful, I'd gladly extend some persistent discounts to you as my thanks for your participation. I can give you an overview of the system first via a live web demonstration - in that way you can take a look before deciding if you want to participate in the test-drive.  Let me know what you think. Thanks for your time, I look forward to hearing back from you!  Best, Ed
